70bfd0ae2cfbf2da192bddd569cf6132 - will there be updates to the contents as well? As HTML5 evolves, I think that's a much bigger concern than "formatting" - that is, such a widely used reference falling out of date with respect to the standards. Example: http://www.diveinto.org/html5/extensibility.html says "a third option which is part of, and tightly integrated into, HTML5 itself: microdata." - microdata hasn't been "part of" HTML5 for quite some time - it's a separate specification that works with / on top of HTML, similar to microformats. I'd assume the pages were quite accessible to begin with, given Mark Pilgrim's background/expertise with accessibility (c.f. previous diveintoaccessibility.org and book Dive Into Accessibility) - were there specific accessibility problems you found? Ah very good. Is there a particular repository you prefer to have updated? I think I've seen several forks. Oh got it. Ah, it wasn't futurefriend.ly then :)

I just use '... IN ('.(join ', ', map '?', @data).')' to get the right number of them has never encountered a more elegant method It's less crass if you're dynamically generating placeholders, and not putting user-supplied data into the query string You could always create a temporary table, insert each item into that table, then do the query with "foo IN (SELECT value FROM that_temporary_table)"

And HTML5 is how much longer, twenty times as long? :/ is ballparking You couldn't test a lot of HTML5 requirements in a cross-browser way, could you?  You'd need something more like Mozilla's mochitests, that can synthesize input and whatnot. How would you do it, then?  Except manually, of course. doesn't want to see anyone try running 100,000 tests manually :P "Generated"? So how many substantively different things did these 15,000 tests actually test?

"Markup conformance requirements that need to be tested and give them a stable identifier that will persist across drafts of the specification." - http://www.w3.org/TR/2010/NOTE-test-methodology-20100128/ i generated about 15000 tests for a css feature yeah, i wrote some python scripts although i wanted to generate more for interaction with svg i tested different combinations of percentages, lengths and keywords, visibility:hidden/visible, and the different values for the feature, for a number of different elements including invalid cases oh and with different images

That's easy, just use the text of the conformance requirement as the identifier 88d4d34a8064a4ff39fd5e144eea7762: I counted 223 requirement statements for <canvas> a while ago so there's going to be quite a lot across the whole spec Lots (I suppose it's more about testable points than about conformance requirements)

HTML5 has lots of features, many different facets to test for each, very detailed requirements for most of them, and some nontrivial interactions among different features so probably the level of test coverage needed is even higher than comparison of length to CSS would imply though to be fair, CSS is also pretty damn complicated CSS has some very complex interactions by design HTML5 has a fair number of complex interactions by accident of history there are many HTML requirements that would be hard to test if the browser itself is your only test tool that doesn't mean you can't do it in a cross-browser way one possible way is to run an external program to synthesize input events, and possibly capture output people have made such tools that work with any given browser, for example for testing Web sites or for general QA of any native application with a GUI of course for any conformance requirement that can be tested by scripting against the DOM, that's the best way to do it

Lack of requirments will come with a huge rathole, at the bottom of which will be the original ratholes but renamed "best practices" So I don't see any possibility for gain here As far as I can tell the main agenda here is that some people don't like the HTML5 draft because it doesn't endorse something that they hold dear to them. notice should not be a problem for prior contributors to html5lib, but may be a headache.  Let me explain. for starters, html5lib is licensed in a way that allows other to take that work and incorporate it into a bigger project under a more restrictive license (say, GPL or proprietary).   With me so far? the same thing is true in a smaller scale.  I contributed some code to html5lib under MIT.  Nothing in my contribution precludes you from having a notice which says "these parts are licensed under MIT, those parts under cc-by".  Doing so does not require you to get my permission. cool b25b6b77a0087ff8385941e5545d32ea: I didn't mean to suggest doing so on the sub-file level. f139aba52f9fa1394b4034a7954b2220: it would be helpful if we can convert the "bad feelings" into tangible arguments. I've emailed a friend at the FSF. My sense is that the W3C is going to demand attribution; I want to quantify the pain that such a demand costs. f139aba52f9fa1394b4034a7954b2220: I certainly intend to include MIT on the set of licenses that this group is OK with. I have no issue with BSD without the advertising clause, or the Apache License.  Both would present similar challenges to html5lib. The Apache License would potentially pose additional problems to LGPLv2 but not LGPLv3. I say potentially, because there is disagreement over this.  My feeling is that when there is disagreement, it is better to avoid the issue. Meanwhile, I'd like to hear a clear answer to the question Karl posed on the mailing list. http://lists.w3.org/Archives/Public/public-html/2009Feb/0062.html

I think GPL compatibility should be an absolute requirement for any licence we choose a480104b0e570389c6f4284a88c7cd9d, even MIT says in the conditions that "The above copyright notice and this permission notice shall be included in all copies or substantial portions of the Software.", and the copyright statement would state the W3C isn't that enough for attribution? a480104b0e570389c6f4284a88c7cd9d, BSD too? a480104b0e570389c6f4284a88c7cd9d, which question? oh, just got the mail 3f2e2531201cfbf853f16f668132eaf2, I agree. Forking the spec should be fine as long as they don't misrepresent the forked copy as being endorsed by the W3C but I think that would be a trademark issue anyway

Google Code has a very limited selection of licences allowed for projects it hosts, and "partly MIT and partly CC-by" is not one of them It's a pain for anyone who wants to use html5lib as part of their project if they have the burden of understanding and following the extra requirements imposed by CC-by (so it's a problem regardless of whether the licences are compatible (i.e. you can mix the code and distribute it all legally)) The practical pain is zero because people can copy-and-paste from the WHATWG version of the spec instead b25b6b77a0087ff8385941e5545d32ea: I'm not sure why the sub-file levels matters - what matters is whether the project as a whole can claim to be usable under the MIT licence or something more complex Another possible use case: Years in the future, some group of people are fed up with the stagnation of HTML5, and they decide to form a (non-W3C, non-WHATWG) working group to develop something informally called HTML6, and want to base their work on the existing HTML5 spec Even less hypothetical: Someone wants to write http://html4all.org/wiki/index.php/HTML_Draft and copy some parts from the HTML5 spec

jgraham: re: http://www.w3.org/community/data-driven-standards/ the advantage, imho, of a community group is to create a place where people can gather - one list that discusses how to technically achieve the goal and document how it is done. We'd like to start building tools that allow folks to just plug in regular expressions that are run on a monthly/quarterly basis... we're thinking of using CommonCrawl to do the first sets of crawls and then utilizing someone like 80legs.com for the next few crawls. We're planning on doing a crawl to see where and how RDFa and Microdata is being used/abused... I've been trying to get something like this going for about 6 months now, but every time we try to partner w/ someone, it falls through... and it's become increasingly difficult to wrangle everyone involved.... so, CG seemed like a good place to gather and promote the ideas. I think we'll use the wiki to gather services and document how to write crawls for each service... probably have a github account in time for crawling template storage... so that you can just copy the crawling template (map/reduce job) to an Amazon Elastic Map Reduce instance and hit "GO!" make sense? a11aabeeceeae6b8cb5d12ea06b56554: do you know how much data dotdotbot has? or dmoz? CommonCrawl has tens of terabytes of data (5 billion pages?) 80legs claims to crawl the entire crawl-able web every 3 months (but does not store the data - they just process as they crawl) - there is also WebGrep - but they don't support regexes, just static string matching. yes, true... but seeing as how nobody really has any public data yet... we have to start somewhere. one of the things we're considering is running a test on each crawling service... to see how representative each one are. s/one are/one is wrt to the other/ 7f9405da4034bf43083e64b57302a8e6 - I remember somebody doing something like that w/ FOAF some time ago, but I can't remember the URL for it... a11aabeeceeae6b8cb5d12ea06b56554: yes, that would be a good alternative as well - but I'm suspect as to how easy it will be to have people install software to crawl the web on our behalf.... I think it's a good idea, just that writing the software and getting a community built around it seems to be more difficult than utilizing these large web crawls. 7f9405da4034bf43083e64b57302a8e6: absolutely, it would be nice to have... one of our engineers tried using gource to do a visualization of some RDF data we had... it was a good idea that was never finished. re: large crawls - representative sample... we're not just concerned about RDFa/Microdata... I think it would be good for the HTML5 spec... allowing features to be killed off more easily (see the latest <time> fiasco - which I agreed w/ the removal of time, but w/o data it's hard to make a case for /any/ removal) re: http://sexchart.org/sexchart.9.43 - that made my eyes bleed.

likes Perl's custom sort syntax, since it encourages use of the spaceship operator my @sorted_by_increasing_age_then_decreasing_height = sort { $a->{age} <=> $b->{age} or $b->{height} <=> $a->{height} } @people; etc -1, 0, or +1 (There's a 'cmp' operator which does the same but with string comparison instead of numeric comparison) b25b6b77a0087ff8385941e5545d32ea: The operators take any type, and always perform the same operation (e.g. a numeric comparison, or a string comparison) regardless of the dynamic type of the variables (which means you never end up with bugs like doing "var count = input.value + 1; // oops, the input was 0 and now count is '01'" like in JS) (It's silly having a language with implicit string<->number conversions and then operators that do very different things depending on whether a value is currently represented as a string or a number) 88d4d34a8064a4ff39fd5e144eea7762: Perl says anything that stringifies to "" or "0" is false, I believe 88d4d34a8064a4ff39fd5e144eea7762: What about the number 0? Perl's rules apply to all types so 0 stringifies to "0", undefined stringifies to "", objects stringify to "HASH(0x7d8220)" (i.e. not false), etc s/objects/object references/ (Perl uses "<", "<=", "==", "<=>" etc for numeric comparisons, and "lt", "le", "eq", "cmp" etc for string comparisons, which is nice and consistent; but then it uses "||" and "&&" for normal C-like-precedence boolean operators, and "or" and "and" for lower-precedence versions of the safe functions, which is a little more confusing) s/safe/same/ Those have C-like precedence, I think Lower precedence means you can write "open $fh, $filename or die" to mean "if (not (open $fh, $filename)) { die; }" in a more concise and threatening way Sadly you can't write "open $fh, $filename or else" It's a built-in function You can define your own, e.g. the Carp module adds carp and croak etc which act like die but a bit different

PHP works the same way.  It's convenient except when it misbehaves and everything breaks. Like, in PHP it's a bad idea to do if (!$str) { /* assume string is empty */ }, because '0' == false. I can't count the number of MediaWiki bugs that's caused. I assume it stole the idea from Perl. Yes. Except when you mean it to be a string and it happens to be exactly '0', it's a headache. Like if (!$_GET['username']) { echo '<strong class=error>You must enter a username!</strong>'; } That means '0' is an invalid username, oops. I think using . for string concatenation makes sense. That far it works. But the boolean casting behavior is wonky. Actually, casting altogether is wonky. '0' == false, false == '', '' != '0' That's even more horrible. At least in PHP it's only literal '' and '0'. Wait, that doesn't even make sense. I meant strings. Of course non-strings have their own rules. Python is strictly typed. Which I have mixed feelings about. It feels kind of excessive to me to have to write things like "Answer is " + str(answer) instead of being able to just use "Answer is " + answer. I have to say, interpolation is really awesome. "Answer is $answer" Strong, strict, whatever. The opposite of dynamic is static. Python has strong dynamic typing. Is there any way in Python to get something like "Foo $bar baz" to interpolate variables?  Something comparably uncluttered? Yeah, but that separates the variables from the place they're put. It's considerably more awkward. Although probably better than loads of " + ". Well, " + foo + ". Another thing that's bitten me in Python is how it concatenates adjacent strings.  Like "foo" "bar" == "foobar".  That's all very nice until you declare an array of lots of strings and forget a comma at the end of the line. Then they silently merge together instead of erroring. It makes sense for C, because there's no way to concatenate strings without a function call. You can just stick in a + . . . Python just uses "and" and "or" across the board.  Much nicer. Also "not" and "in". Down with punctuation! I used to use them in an attempt to emulate Python, but other MediaWiki developers mostly prefer && and ||, so I go with the flow (at least for MW). It's kind of like this note from our style guide: "Homesick C developers write null as NULL because they want to believe that it is a macro defined as ((void*)0). This is not necessary." I like the "threatening". Concise is, of course, typical of Perl. We seem to be mostly Python people here, is that a coincidence? b25b6b77a0087ff8385941e5545d32ea, I think it's a function, not a keyword, no? (I could be totally wrong.) 1f8387eb43f131d7c309a90a4e36b5cb, you're a Python person if you prefer Python to Perl, regardless of whether you actually use or know either. Hixie is a Perl person, and apparently so is ab7faae5d7b250ea8606486575f8f79c. Well, Ruby is much less popular overall than Perl or Python. At least last I checked. It seems to have gotten more popular over the last couple of years, but Python and Perl are much better-established. (especially Perl) If I were learning a new language, it would be Lisp or Haskell or something.

Do they say "SHOULD" or "should"? likes the HTML5 style of SHOULD/MUST/etc usage, since it makes it clear what behaviour needs to be tested Sometimes I think other specifications are mostly written for users (who want to know how they can expect their implementations to behave) and implementors (who want to know how their implementations should behave), neither of whom care much about the difference between 'should' and 'must' whereas something like HTML5 is also written for test writers, who do care about subtle differences between conformance requirements I'd expect they're hurt mostly by the lack of defined error handling when there's duplicate names, rather than by the use of should/must That seems largely independent of any should/must confusion e.g. the JSON spec requires quotes around keys, but lots of JSON implementations let you turn that off because it saves some bytes and it works in some parsers and it seems they don't really care about interoperability On an unrelated topic: Automated tests are great, but running them on a wide variety of web browsers is time-consuming. What we could do is sign up to an online ad system that lets you put arbitrary HTML in your ads, and then immediately get hundreds of thousands of testers with no effort and very low financial cost (and the HTML we put in the ads would be executing the tests and then sending the results (plus UA strings etc) back to the central server) b25b6b77a0087ff8385941e5545d32ea: Uh, not quite sure what you mean b25b6b77a0087ff8385941e5545d32ea: But that would be extremely hard and would take years to build up and to get on enough sites to get significant numbers of visitors was inspired by abarth's work on this :-) 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: Haven't you seen any World War 2 movies?
